dismissalComment.html: Gone! got him! Another Bravo special! A slow full-length delivery! Kaif is completely beaten and the ball squeezes past his waft to disturb the furniture. Yuvraj Singh can understand Kaif's pain... A similar delivery had got him in that exciting second match.

dismissalText.commentary: Yuvraj Singh c †Baugh b Edwards 52 (78b 5x4 0x6) SR: 66.66

dismissalComment.html: short of a good length delivery, pitched close to the off stump line and slanting away from the left-hander, line and length was just perfect, Yuvraj has a poke at it, like a stranger in a strange land searching for the mythical unicorn, ball moves away just enough to clip the outside edge, Baugh quickly moves across to his left and takes a good low catch - that's a big wicket!

dismissalComment.html: Oh dear! Bravo gets another wicket courtesy his famous slower ball!  Released between his thumb and the forefinger and it loops in the air towards the off and middle stump and even as Agarkar's high back lift descends, the ball dips, grips the surface, turns in past the blade to take out the leg stump!

dismissalComment.html: gone! super catch! short of length and outside the off stump, Sehwag has a go at it again, threw his hands at it and the ball was ascending over Gayle, at covers, but Gayle times his jump perfectly to pouch the ball. The danger man Sehwag is gone!

headshotImage.caption: SK Raina headshot
headshotImage.longCaption: SK Raina headshot

dismissalComment.html: gone! short of length and a foot outside the offstump, Raina gets back and across and goes for a square-cut, rather a square-slash, gets the edge which flies fast  above head-high and to the right of Sarwan, at first slip, who pouches it safely. A very good catch and now India in trouble here.

commentTextItems.html: there it is! tossed up on the stumps, bowled from round the wickets, Hinds quickly goes down on one knee and slogs it away to the midwicket fence - crowd goes wild, West Indies win by 6 wickets and they take the series 3-1.

commentPostTextItems.html: They have done it in style and now it's time to party! West Indian players rush on to the field to congratulate Bravo and Hinds, the noise is deafening and there are colored paper fliers dripping from all directions, they are celebrating it football style

The West Indies players go for a victory walk around the arena thanking the fans for their support, a memorable day for West Indian cricket, fans and players as well and surely this win will be remembered for a long time to come.
For the latest bulletin on today's play, features and other stories please visit www.cricinfo.com
Do write in with any feedback at http://www.cricinfo.com/commentary.html
Gayle got them off to a fantastic start, he clobbered the bowlers all over the park, the one handed six which he hit over midwicket was a gem.
Once they got the start the batsmen showed amazing character, they played each and every ball on merit, something unheard off in West  Indies cricket for the last couple of years.

Lara came in when they were in a spot of bother but he lived up to the challenge, started off watchfully and then opened up once the writing was on the wall, Bravo played the perfect foil to Lara and he along with Wavell Hinds took West Indies to a memorable series win.
India on the other hand never got things going, they have lot of thinking to do and Sunday presents an opportunity to redeem some pride.
Bravo has been awarded the man-of-the-match for his brilliant all-round performance( 3 wickets and a match winning innings of 61).
We will be back on Sunday with all the live action, for the time being though this is Sajan Nair along with Sriram Veera signing off - Good bye and good luck.

stories.title: Lara and Bravo take Windies to glory
stories.subTitle: West Indies v India, 4th ODI, Trinidad
stories.summary: Playing what will probably be his penultimate one-day game at his home ground of Queen's Park Oval, Brian Lara produced a glorious matchwinning 69 as West Indies romped home to a six-wicket win

stories.title: 'My feet are on the ground' - Lara
stories.subTitle: Fourth ODI post-match press conference
stories.summary: Brian Lara's "feet are on the ground" as he speaks to media persons after winning the one-day series against India at Port-of-Spain

stories.title: 'We had calmer heads than India' - Lara
stories.subTitle: West Indies v India, 4th ODI, Trinidad
stories.summary: After today's clash, a largely one-sided affair that sealed the series, Brian Lara spoke about the crucial challenges West Indies will face in the months to come

stories.title: 'The boys are not deflated' - Dravid
stories.subTitle: West Indies v India, 4th ODI, Trinidad
stories.summary: Rahul Dravid isn't someone to take defeat lightly but he had no qualms in spelling out the exact reasons for the stumble

stories.title: The road to 2007
stories.subTitle: Fourth ODI post-match talk on Cricinfo audio
stories.summary: While West Indies have shown with this series win that they won't be pushovers in the World Cup, where did it go wrong for India? An analysis on Cricinfo audio

stories.title: India get a taste of their own medicine
stories.subTitle: West Indies v India, 4th ODI, Trinidad
stories.summary: After three games that twisted and turned, West Indies finally broke away and gradually, like a giant wave gaining momentum, crashed into India
stories.byline: The Verdict by Siddhartha Vaidyanathan in Trinidad

stories.title: Lara's mastery against spin
stories.subTitle: West Indies v India, 4th ODI, Trinidad
stories.summary: Lara scored 53 runs off 63 balls against spin and only 16 runs off 37 balls against the fast bowlers. At every opportunity, Lara used his feet to smother the spin and bounce
